"1294–1341","1311–Female":"1311–Overleden","1322–1386":"1322–1386","1295–1341":"1295–1341","–Male":"Overleden","1319–1400":"1319–1400","1286–1349":"1286–1349","1274–1348":"1274–1348","1341":"1341","1286":"1286","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","about 1318":"circa 1318","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1311":"1311","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England"},"en":{"1294–1341":"1294–1341","1311–Female":"1311–Deceased","1322–1386":"1322–1386","1295–1341":"1295–1341","–Male":"Deceased","1319–1400":"1319–1400","1286–1349":"1286–1349","1274–1348":"1274–1348","1341":"1341","1286":"1286","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","about 1318":"about 1318","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1311":"1311","1453":"1453","1386":"1386","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Harley, Shropshire, England":"Harley, Shropshire, England","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places called Harley (Shropshire, Yorkshire). The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ or <i>hær</i> + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’, later replaced by <i>lēah</i>.","Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> without the initial <i>F-</i>. This name has also become   Herley   and   Hurley  . Compare   Arrell   and   Harrell  .","Scottish (Fife): habitational name from any of several places called Harlaw in Midlothian, Peeblesshire, and Berwickshire, named in Older Scots with <i>hare</i> ‘gray’ + <i>law</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Herley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Art, Cormac.","Irish: variant of   Hurley  , probably via   Herlihy  .","English: variant of   Harley   or   Hurley  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":21,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":34,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":43,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan de Harley was born in 1294, in Harley, Shropshire, England, her father, Sir Robert H